SIMPLE: thought
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thought
<hw>Thought</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <def><pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> of
<er>Think</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thought</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Thought
<hw>Thought</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>⟦thorn⟧oght</ets>,
<ets>⟦thorn⟧ouht</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦thorn⟧⟦omac⟧ht</ets>,
ge<ets>⟦thorn⟧⟦omac⟧ht</ets>, fr. <ets>⟦thorn⟧encean</ets> to think;
akin to D. ge<ets>dachte</ets> thought, MHG. <ets>d⟦amac⟧ht</ets>,
ge<ets>d⟦amac⟧ht</ets>, Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧⟦omac⟧ttr</ets>,
<ets>⟦thorn⟧⟦omac⟧tti</ets>. See <er>Think</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of thinking; the exercise of the mind in any of its higher
forms; reflection; cogitation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Thought</qex> can not be superadded to matter, so as in any
sense to render it true that matter can become cogitative.</q>
<rj><qau>Dr. T. Dwight.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Meditation; serious consideration.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pride, of all others the most dangerous fault,⟦br⟧
Proceeds from want of sense or want of <qex>thought</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is thought; an idea; a mental conception,
whether an opinion, judgment, fancy, purpose, or intention.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus Bethel spoke, who always speaks his <qex>thought</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why do you keep alone, . . . ⟦br⟧
Using those <qex>thoughts</qex> which should indeed have died⟦br⟧
With them they think on?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Thoughts</qex> come crowding in so fast upon me, that my only
difficulty is to choose or to reject.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All their <qex>thoughts</qex> are against me for evil.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. lvi. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Solicitude; anxious care; concern.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hawis was put in trouble, and died with <qex>thought</qex> and
anguish before his business came to an end.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Take no <qex>thought</qex> for your life, what ye shall eat, or
what ye shall drink.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. vi. 25.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A small degree or quantity; a trifle; <as>as, a
<ex>thought</ex> longer; a <ex>thought</ex> better.</as></def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If the hair were a <qex>thought</qex> browner.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Thought</xex>, in philosophical usage now somewhat
current, denotes the capacity for, or the exercise of, the very highest
intellectual functions, especially those usually comprehended under
judgment.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This [faculty], to which I gave the name of the ⟦ldquo⟧elaborative
faculty,⟦rdquo⟧ -- the faculty of relations or comparison, --
constitutes what is properly denominated <qex>thought</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Idea; conception; imagination; fancy; conceit;
notion; supposition; reflection; consideration; meditation;
contemplation; cogitation; deliberation.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thoughtful</ent>⟦br⟧
